<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,222,788]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,350,474,499]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species occurs from northeast to southeast 
<collectingCountry box="[898,966,474,498]" name="Brazil" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Brazil</collectingCountry>
to south 
<collectingCountry box="[1072,1176,475,499]" name="Paraguay" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1232,1331,475,499]" name="Uruguay" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
, and also in eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[267,318,511,534]" name="Peru" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Peru</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[373,458,510,534]" name="Bolivia" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, occupying Cerrado, Caatinga and Chaco biomes (
<bibRefCitation author="Gardner" box="[1029,1191,510,534]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refString="Gardner, A. L. (2007) American marsupials. In: Gardner, A. L. (Ed), Mammals of South America, Volume 1. The University of Chicago Press, Chicago, pp. 1 - 126." type="book" year="2007">
Gardner 
<number box="[1130,1191,510,534]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). These are the northwesternmost records of 
<taxonomicName box="[419,512,547,571]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Gracilinanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="agilis">
<emphasis box="[419,512,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">G. agilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
along with those of 
<bibRefCitation box="[741,976,546,571]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refString="Bezerra, A. M. R., Carmignotto, A. P. &amp; Rodrigues, F. H. G. (2009) Small non-volant mammals of na ecotone region between the Cerrado hotspot and the Amazonian rainforest, with comments on their taxonomy and distribution. Zoological Studies, 48, 861 - 874." type="journal article">
Bezerra 
<emphasis box="[835,892,547,571]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[906,968,546,570]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2009.0">2009</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,222,788]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,388,582,607]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Natural history.</emphasis>
Forty-seven individuals (
<specimenCount box="[681,785,582,606]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="adult">
<number box="[681,710,582,606]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="41.0">41</number>
adults
</specimenCount>
and six juveniles) were captured either in Sherman traps placed on the ground (n = 
<number box="[447,476,618,642]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="29.0">29</number>
) or in the understory (n = 
<number box="[772,802,618,642]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="13.0">13</number>
), and in pitfall traps (n = 
<number box="[1088,1104,618,642]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="5.0">5</number>
). Almost all individuals of 
<taxonomicName class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Gracilinanus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="agilis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">G. agilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were captured in natural forest fragments at FLV, either enclosed in the matrix of pristine Cerrado or in cultivated lands, and only two were captured in alluvial forests at PEC. Seven lactating females and six juveniles were captured in 
<date box="[283,470,726,750]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2008-09">
September 
<number box="[410,470,726,750]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="2008.0">2008</number>
</date>
.
</paragraph>
